            <pb facs="#TL-0530.jpg" n="part4_p056.jpg" xml:id="img_0056" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p056.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_56_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>-525
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>and this means the esthical contents-come? How can we know, in a special moment, what to do?
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>If this is understood and accepted, then we are driven to a very difficult alternative.
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>This alternative is the conconditional character of the form of ethics, and theWditional character
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>of the content of ethics. Ethics are dependent on culture; they change with every special
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>H A
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>situation; they have a certain kind of daicnuity in period which have,continuity themselves;
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>they tend to get into complete dissolution in period in which the fundamental principles
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_56_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>disintegrate. This is the argument for the relative of ethics. And of course, if you look at
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>the history of religion and the history of culture, you find much evidence for kthical relativism,
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>oudence which cannot be derived, not only with respect to lrimitive cultures, or with respect
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>to different high cultural groups, such as the Asiatic and the European, but also with respect to
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>national and sociological difference within one group, as for instance American culture. The
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>are comparatively homogeneous, if you compare them
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/> lthical contents, although they
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>with the contents in Asia, or Africa (the primities), are nevertheless very much disferentiated
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>with respect to social groups, local conditions, and historical tradition. All this has a
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>tremendous influence on exhical contents, and this relativism goes even deeper into the individual
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>who, if he is autonomous, makes decisions about his esthical decision about his moral attitude¬
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_12" n="N012"/>you remember I ’defined morale as the matter itself and ethics as the science of this matter.
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_2_tl_13" n="N013"/>And they are different, and nevertheless they can be justified.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_56_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>Now the anxious question, which is very often asked about this point, is the
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>question of a relativism which makes not only community impossible—how can you live
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>together if the esthical contents are completely relative and different?—but also with respect
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>to the individual himself: what is the situation if you don’t know what to do if you are in the
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>pross-section of different cultural lnfluences—and everybody is, to a great extent.
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>We all are in the cross-section of at least humanistic secularism, Christian traditions—and
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>Monsieur Mounard
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>pour entendre
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>Monsieur le Comte de lʼhonneur de
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>mais je prends mon frere,
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>le prêter de
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_14" n="N014"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_15" n="N015"/>dʼacquerir que
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_16" n="N016"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_17" n="N017"/>de votre beau;
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_18" n="N018"/>dans cette teinte valeur, que je nʼai pas
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_19" n="N019"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_20" n="N020"/>a-t-elle
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_21" n="N021"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_22" n="N022"/>lʼauteur dʼune manière vieuse
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_23" n="N023"/>Monsieur, que je ne lʼai
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_24" n="N024"/>de Vous avez
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_25" n="N025"/>dʼordre pour les
               <lb facs="#facs_56_tr_1_tl_26" n="N026"/>Monsieur
            </p>
            
